04970nam a22007575i 9780292799233DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20212009txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927992337 a10.7560/7199892doi  a(DE-B1597)587863  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aTX840.B3 ǂb R462 2009eb 7aSOC0550002bisacsh04a641.57841 aEngelhardt, Elizabeth S. D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRepublic of Barbecue :bStories Beyond the Brisket /cElizabeth S. D. Engelhardt. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2009  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt's no overstatement to say that the state of Texas is a republic of barbecue. Whether it's brisket, sausage, ribs, or chicken, barbecue feeds friends while they catch up, soothes tensions at political events, fuels community festivals, sustains workers of all classes, celebrates brides and grooms, and even supports churches. Recognizing just how central barbecue is to Texas's cultural life, Elizabeth Engelhardt and a team of eleven graduate students from the University of Texas at Austin set out to discover and describe what barbecue has meant to Texans ever since they first smoked a beef brisket. Republic of Barbecue presents a fascinating, multifaceted portrait of the world of barbecue in Central Texas. The authors look at everything from legendary barbecue joints in places such as Taylor and Lockhart to feedlots, ultra-modern sausage factories, and sustainable forests growing hardwoods for barbecue pits. They talk to pit masters and proprietors, who share the secrets of barbecue in their own words. Like side dishes to the first-person stories, short essays by the authors explore a myriad of barbecue's themes—food history, manliness and meat, technology, nostalgia, civil rights, small-town Texas identity, barbecue's connection to music, favorite drinks such as Big Red, Dr. Pepper, Shiner Bock, and Lone Star beer—to mention only a few. An ode to Texas barbecue in films, a celebration of sports and barbecue, and a pie chart of the desserts that accompany brisket all find homes in the sidebars of the book, while photographic portraits of people and places bring readers face-to-face with the culture of barbecue.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aBarbecuingzSouthern StatesvAnecdotes. 0aBarbecuingzSouthern States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh1 aAbrahams, Marsha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBendele, Marvin C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenke, Gavin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBusch, Andrew M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCovey, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCroke, Dave, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdge, John T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngelhardt, Elizabeth S. D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaupt, Melanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKocurek, Carly A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPowell, Lisa Jordan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRamirez, Remy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71998940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292799233423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292799233/or